<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Source for Succession Planting Seed Mixes</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The best succession mixes are built around timing, not just variety.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, Johnny’s Selected Seeds and High Mowing Organic Seeds are the best sources for succession planting because they make it easier to choose crops by maturity and replanting intervals. Botanical Interests is a solid option for simpler, pre-built mixes that are easy to use.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Succession planting works when crops are timed to follow each other. That depends less on having a mix and more on choosing the right sequence of varieties.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best seed sources make that easier by helping you understand what to plant next and when.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Picks: Best Sources for Succession Planting</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> Johnny’s Selected Seeds — strongest for comparing maturity and building custom successions.</li>
      <li><strong>Best organic option:</strong> High Mowing Organic Seeds — reliable crops with consistent performance across plantings.</li>
      <li><strong>Best simple mixes:</strong> Botanical Interests — easy-to-use blends for greens and continuous harvest crops.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The right source helps you build a sequence of crops, not just plant everything at once.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Johnny’s Is the Best Overall Choice</h2>

  <p>
    Johnny’s Selected Seeds stands out because it makes timing visible.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is especially useful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>comparing days-to-maturity across similar crops</li>
    <li>choosing early, mid, and late varieties</li>
    <li>building staggered plantings intentionally</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This allows you to create your own succession plan instead of relying on pre-made mixes that may not fit your timing.
  </p>

  <p>
    For example, pairing faster and slower crops is much easier when you can clearly identify <a href="/guides/best-seed-company-for-fast-maturing-varieties/">which varieties mature quickly</a> and which take longer.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why High Mowing Works Well for Repeated Plantings</h2>

  <p>
    High Mowing Organic Seeds is a strong option when consistency matters across multiple plantings.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its varieties tend to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>germinate reliably across different conditions</li>
    <li>perform consistently throughout the season</li>
    <li>focus on productive, practical crops</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This is especially useful when planting the same crop several times and expecting similar results each round.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Pre-Made Mixes Make Sense</h2>

  <p>
    Botanical Interests and similar companies offer pre-built mixes that simplify succession planting.
  </p>

  <p>
    These are most useful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>leafy greens that can be harvested continuously</li>
    <li>gardeners who want a low-effort approach</li>
    <li>quick replanting without detailed planning</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The tradeoff is less control over timing, but more convenience.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Makes Succession Planting Work</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Staggered maturity.</strong> Crops need to be spaced out in time, not just planted together.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable germination.</strong> Each planting needs to establish quickly to keep the cycle moving.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Clear replanting windows.</strong> Knowing when to re-seed is more important than what mix you use.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good seed sources support these decisions instead of leaving them to guesswork.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Many Succession Plans Break Down</h2>

  <p>
    The most common issue is timing drift.
  </p>

  <p>
    This happens when:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>crops take longer than expected to mature</li>
    <li>replanting happens too late</li>
    <li>later plantings do not finish before conditions change</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These problems often show up in the second half of the season, when there is less time to recover.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why it helps to understand <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">whether later plantings will mature before the first frost</a> so the full sequence holds together.
  </p>
</section>

