<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most People Get Wrong</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>They rely on mixes instead of timing.</strong> The sequence matters more than the blend.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>They plant everything at once.</strong> Succession planting only works when plantings are staggered.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>They ignore late-season constraints.</strong> Later plantings are the most likely to fail without planning.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Do</h2>

  <p>
    For most gardens, using a seed company like Johnny’s or High Mowing to build your own succession plan is more effective than relying entirely on pre-made mixes.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Succession planting works best when you control the timing.
  </p>
</section>

